Extended thinkingLearn more about extended thinking, including manual mode, tool use, and prompt caching.Effort parameterControl how thoroughly Claude responds with the effort parameter.Was this page helpful?Supported modelsHow adaptive thinking worksHow to use adaptive thinkingAdaptive thinking with the effort parameterStreaming with adaptive thinkingAdaptive vs manual vs disabled thinkingImportant considerationsValidation changesPrompt cachingTuning thinking behaviorCost controlWorking with thinking blocksSummarized thinkingControlling thinking displayThinking encryptionPricingAdditional topicsNext steps', 'At high and max effort levels, Claude may think more extensively and can be more likely to exhaust the max_tokens budget. If you observe stop_reason: "max_tokens" in responses, consider increasing max_tokens to give the model more room, or lowering the effort level.
Working with thinking blocks
The following concepts apply to all models that support extended thinking, regardless of whether you use adaptive or manual mode.
Summarized thinking
With extended thinking enabled, the Messages API for Claude 4 models returns a summary of Claude's full thinking process. Summarized thinking provides the full intelligence benefits of extended thinking, while preventing misuse. This is the default behavior on Claude 4 models when the display field on the thinking configuration is unset or set to "summarized". On Claude Opus 4.7 and Claude Mythos Preview, display defaults to "omitted" instead, so you must set display: "summarized" explicitly to receive summarized thinking.']
